    {
      "id": "004c361a_25e93236",
      "file_path": "utils/checkstyle-suppressions.xml",
      "patchset_number": 3,
      "line": null,
      "message": "I'll leave that up to you.  Currently, there are two sets of tests, both verifying that the code skips over fields and method names that contain \"$\".  The first set of tests do it by simply passing the names into a validation method, while the second set of tests do it by actually having fields and methods with \"$\" in their names.  The former can be done without the checkstyle suppression, while the latter cannot.",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 811,
        "name": "Jim Hahn",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "jrh3@att.com",
        "username": "jrh3"
      },
      "updated": "2019-02-07 14:21:31.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": "89cf3f6c_9d5deb64",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "id": "dd8f8519_faf79fc7",
      "file_path": "utils/checkstyle-suppressions.xml",
      "patchset_number": 3,
      "line": null,
      "message": "I take that back; there's only one set of tests.  So, yes, the checkstyle suppression is needed, if we're to have 100% test coverage.",
      "author": {
